`pipeline_refactored.py` written to trial-2 workdir. Here's what changed and why:

| Original | Refactored | Rationale |
|---|---|---|
| `DB_PATH`, `LOG_FILE` hardcoded at module level | `Config` NamedTuple reads `PIPELINE_LOG_FILE` / `PIPELINE_DB_PATH` from `os.environ` | Environment-driven config for all paths; dropped the dead Postgres credentials |
| `INSERT INTO errors VALUES ('%s', '%s', %d)" % (...)` | `INSERT INTO errors (dt, message, count) VALUES (?, ?, ?)` with `executemany` | Parameterized queries eliminate SQL injection; explicit column list is self-documenting |
| Monolithic `proc_data()` — 121 lines, all crammed | `read_log_lines` (Extract) → `parse_log_lines` + `aggregate_*` (Transform) → `store_*` + `generate_report` (Load) | Clear ETL boundary; each function ≤30 lines, testable in isolation |
| `line.split(" ")` with index magic + manual string concat | `LOG_LINE_RE`, `USER_ACTION_RE`, `API_LATENCY_RE` — three compiled regexes with named groups | Robust against whitespace variation; intent is obvious from pattern |
| No types, no docs | Full typing (5 NamedTuples: `Config`, `LogEntry`, `ApiCall`, `ErrorCount`, `ParsedLogs`) + module- and function-level docstrings | IDE + mypy friendly |
| HTML built with raw `+` (no escaping) | `_html_escape()` applied to user-facing message and endpoint values | Prevents HTML injection from log data |
| `f.close()` without `with` | `with open(...)` for both read and write | Guaranteed cleanup on any code path |
| Sample-data block inline at module level | `_ensure_sample_log()` — extracted to its own function | Same trigger condition, separate concern |
